issue.body:
(@zebambam and I confident enough these are impractical to exploit that we can make the issue public.)

For context, see https://github.com/zcash/zcash/issues/1281. This is a related but separate issue I noticed while trying to come up with a way to exploit that one. The tl;dr is `CNode` implements its own reference counting and that seems to be broken in at least a couple ways.

The first and probably-not-exploitable way is that `FindNode()` (in net.cpp) returns a copy of a pointer to a `CNode` without incrementing the reference count. The only place the returned pointers get dereferenced are in RPCs, (in rpc/net.cpp), e.g. in `disconnectnode()`:

```
    CNode* pNode = FindNode(params[0].get_str());
    if (pNode == NULL)
        throw JSONRPCError(RPC_CLIENT_NODE_NOT_CONNECTED, "Node not found in connected nodes");

    pNode->fDisconnect = true;
```

The `cs_vNodes` lock is not held here, so given godlike control over the scheduler, you could freeze it just before the `pNode->fDisconnect = true;` line, have the peer send an invalid message and let the other threads run to process that invalid message and disconnect and free the memory, now `pNode->fDisconnect = true` writes to freed memory.

The second way it's broken is in `ConnectNode()` in net.cpp:

```
...
        // Add node
        CNode* pnode = new CNode(hSocket, addrConnect, pszDest ? pszDest : "", false);
        pnode->AddRef();

        {
            LOCK(cs_vNodes);
            vNodes.push_back(pnode);
        }

        pnode->nTimeConnected = GetTime();

        return pnode;
...
```

It has added a count for the reference in `vNodes` vector but not the returned pointer. The returned pointer ends up in `OpenNetworkConnection()` :

```
...
    CNode* pnode = ConnectNode(addrConnect, pszDest);
    boost::this_thread::interruption_point();

    if (!pnode)
        return false;
    if (grantOutbound)
        grantOutbound->MoveTo(pnode->grantOutbound);
    pnode->fNetworkNode = true;
   // *****
    if (fOneShot)
        pnode->fOneShot = true;
...
```

`cs_vNodes` is not held at this point AFAICT.

There's potential for a use-after-free here but again I think it's really unlikely. The scheduler needs to do a *lot* at the line marked `*****` and `fOneShot` needs to be true, then `pnode->fOneShot = true;` might write to freed memory. Because:

- At this point, the reference count is 1.
- By inspecting `ThreadSocketHandler()` we can see it will free the memory of any CNode in `vNodes` whose (a) fDisconnect is true, (b) reference count is 1, and (c) pnode->fNetworkNode is true. That last point is why this only works if the thread gets interrupted at `*****`, not at the `boost::this_thread::interruption_point();` point which would be more convenient for the attacker.
- If you had godlike control of the scheduler, you could arrange for all of that to happen by having the peer send an invalid message, because `ProcessMessages()` returns false and then it calls CloseSocketDisconnect() which sets `fDisconnect` to true. Then let `ThreadSocketHandler` do its thing to free the memory, then let `OpenNetworkConnection()` continue.

The reason we need `pnode->fNetworkNode` to be true is in ThreadSocketHandler it does:

```
if (pnode->fDisconnect | ... {
...
                    // hold in disconnected pool until all refs are released
                    if (pnode->fNetworkNode || pnode->fInbound)
                        pnode->Release(); // <--- this decrements the reference count
                    vNodesDisconnected.push_back(pnode);
...
```
I really don't understand the logic of that (are pointers to non-`fNetworkNode` non-`fInbound` CNodes in vNodes not counted as references?), but in any case we need that `pnode->fNetworkNode` to be true so that the reference count will be zero in the code just below that actually frees the memory.

Note that the attacker needs to coerce the victim node into making a connection to their node somehow, and they need to do that each time they want to roll the dice with the scheduler so it's probably impractical to exploit. I'm not even 100% sure the connection is fully alive at this point but it seems like `ThreadMessageHandler()` will be polling for messages.

I couldn't find anything else aside from these two issues (by searching for all use of `CNode *`) but it's probably worth replacing this weird manual reference counting with smart pointers or something... especially since it's in network code.

